node.text: Meghan Markle and Prince Harry are ready to take their next steps back into an intentionally public life. 🙏 With their parental leave coming to an end, they are preparing for a busy fall and winter as many of the programs they've been working on behind the scenes kick into action. "They're a couple who do very well in those moments of human interaction. They need to be on the ground," Omid Scobie tells PEOPLE in this week's issue. node.text: Miranda McKeon is marking a major milestone — she's halfway through chemotherapy for breast cancer. 🙏 The 19-year-old actress was diagnosed in mid-June with breast cancer, an extremely rare case for a teenager, and started her first four rounds of chemotherapy a month later. The initial rounds consisted of two drugs, adriamycin and cytoxan, that McKeon was thrilled to leave behind, and her next (and hopefully final) four rounds of chemotherapy will be with a drug called taxol, which she's hoping will be "a bit easier." Tap the bio link for her story. | #Regram @miranda.mckeon

node.text: Mae Whitman says she is "proud" to be pansexual. 🏳️‍🌈 The Good Girls and Parenthood alum revealed her sexuality while speaking out about her Disney Channel animated series, The Owl House, and how it showcases LGBTQIA representation. "I wish I had such incredible characters like Amity and Luz in my life when I was growing up. Queer representation is so so so important," Whitman wrote. "I know ppl might be unfamiliar with what pansexual means; for me it means I know I can fall in love with people of all genders. This is the word that fits me best 🌈 and I'm proud+happy to be part of the Bi+ community :,)." ❤️ | #Regram @mistergarf

node.text: Selma Blair is sharing happy news — after years in a painful multiple sclerosis flare, she's now in remission. 🙏 "My prognosis is great. I'm in remission.
